    <h1>Page Background Color</h1>
    <p>Can be attained by adding class to the &lt;body&gt; tag. This can be done manually, or via Rails magic. A page with color specified in the &lt;body&gt; will have its entire background set to a certain color -- no matter how tall the page gets.</p>
    <p>The following classes are available:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><code>wrap-color-white</code> (default)</li>
      <li><code>wrap-color-black</code></li>
      <li><code>wrap-color-ltGrey</code></li>
      <li><code>wrap-color-dkGrey</code></li>
      <li><code>wrap-color-primary</code></li>
      <li><code>wrap-color-secondary</code></li>
    </ul>
    <p>The classes above should be applied to either the &lt;body&gt; or &lt;div class="full-bleed"&gt;. Any other elements can be given a colored background as per the specs below.</p>
  </div> <!-- end: .content -->

  <div class="content content-island">
    <h1>Element Background Color</h1>
    <p>Can be attained by adding class to any element tag. This can be a gridded item of any size, or any other block level element.</p>
    <p>The following classes are available:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><code>bg-color-white</code> (default)</li>
      <li><code>bg-color-black</code></li>
      <li><code>bg-color-ltGrey</code></li>
      <li><code>bg-color-dkGrey</code></li>
      <li><code>bg-color-primary</code></li>
      <li><code>bg-color-secondary</code></li>
    </ul>
    <p>When the classes above are assigned, the colors of content within are setup to match via the backgrounds.scss file.</p>

    <div class="bg-color-primary" style="padding: 28px 20px 0; margin: 0 0 20px 0; text-align: center; overflow: hidden;">
